00:09:33.099 --> 00:09:39.340
OK, so we are here to talk about text analysis.

00:09:39.340 --> 00:09:42.539
It's very, so I've been working in tooling for text analysis

00:09:42.539 --> 00:09:44.460
for about 10 years.

00:09:44.460 --> 00:09:46.940
And it's a very interesting time to be

00:09:46.979 --> 00:09:48.700
thinking about text analysis.

00:09:48.700 --> 00:09:52.979
Because even 10 years ago, people

00:09:52.979 --> 00:09:55.739
are building tools for being able to do

00:09:55.739 --> 00:09:59.739
quantitative analysis of text of all kinds.

00:09:59.739 --> 00:10:04.020
We have some projects I know people have worked in

00:10:04.020 --> 00:10:08.179
are things like surveys, things like social media data,

00:10:08.179 --> 00:10:12.859
things like reports of various kinds, say, from companies.

00:10:12.859 --> 00:10:16.260
And one thing that I think is we know

00:10:16.260 --> 00:10:23.340
that we can see is that dealing with text data is,

00:10:23.340 --> 00:10:25.659
there's information latent.

00:10:25.659 --> 00:10:27.900
There's information in the text data sets.

00:10:27.900 --> 00:10:31.739
But it can be uncertain, how can we get it out?

00:10:31.739 --> 00:10:34.859
How can we begin to analyze the text data

00:10:34.859 --> 00:10:37.659
and get the information that is out of it?

00:10:37.659 --> 00:10:40.820
Often, if you have quantitative training,

00:10:40.820 --> 00:10:46.340
if you took statistics, if you learned data analysis,

00:10:46.340 --> 00:10:51.099
often what you learn on are nice rectangles of data.

00:10:51.099 --> 00:10:53.460
And maybe they're all numbers.

00:10:53.460 --> 00:10:59.140
And how do we apply these kinds of quantitative training

00:10:59.140 --> 00:11:03.179
to text data, which you can think of as unstructured data?

00:11:03.179 --> 00:11:08.460
There's information in there, but the data

00:11:08.460 --> 00:11:11.419
is not structured in a table format,

00:11:11.419 --> 00:11:13.539
like what you might have in a spreadsheet.

00:11:13.539 --> 00:11:17.219
So often, in our quantitative training,

00:11:17.219 --> 00:11:21.859
we don't learn how to deal with text.

00:11:21.859 --> 00:11:25.219
And now, in the maybe past two years,

00:11:25.219 --> 00:11:29.460
we start to see more tools based on text data,

00:11:29.460 --> 00:11:35.020
like LLMs, the chat GPT, and similar other kinds of tools

00:11:35.020 --> 00:11:45.179
that are trained on enormous quantities, collections

00:11:45.179 --> 00:11:46.059
of text.

00:11:46.059 --> 00:11:49.580
And as someone who has your own data that may be text,

00:11:49.580 --> 00:11:51.260
you're like, how does this impact me?

00:11:51.260 --> 00:11:53.500
How can I use these kinds of tools

00:11:53.500 --> 00:11:55.539
or understand these kinds of tools?

00:11:55.539 --> 00:11:57.179
So that is what we're going to do today.

00:11:57.179 --> 00:12:01.500
So the point, the goal here today

00:12:01.500 --> 00:12:06.659
is that it would be that if you have not dealt with text data,

00:12:06.659 --> 00:12:08.739
you can take these first steps.

00:12:08.739 --> 00:12:11.179
And it is not everything for today,

00:12:11.179 --> 00:12:15.780
but it is the first step so that you can move forward and learn

00:12:15.780 --> 00:12:17.340
how to deal with text data.

00:12:20.260 --> 00:12:26.619
So I want to make the argument that using tidy data

00:12:26.619 --> 00:12:31.659
principles with your text gives you a step up

00:12:31.659 --> 00:12:36.619
in being able to deal with this fluently, quickly,

00:12:36.619 --> 00:12:41.700
with greater fluency than other kinds of tools.

00:12:41.700 --> 00:12:46.580
So if you are familiar, if you have learned R a little bit,

00:12:46.580 --> 00:12:51.099
you may have heard about tools that are called tidy,

00:12:51.099 --> 00:12:52.960
things like the tidyverse.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:58.479
So these are sets of packages that adopt tidy data principles.

00:12:58.479 --> 00:13:03.520
If you come from a SQL background,

00:13:03.520 --> 00:13:10.280
it's the same thing as the rules of normalized tables,

00:13:10.280 --> 00:13:13.280
that every observation is a row.

00:13:13.280 --> 00:13:17.159
If you take a new observation, instead of adding a new column,

00:13:17.159 --> 00:13:18.559
no, you add a new row.

00:13:18.559 --> 00:13:24.200
So you say, OK, I am going to take the temperature outside

00:13:24.200 --> 00:13:26.320
today, tomorrow, the next day.

00:13:26.320 --> 00:13:31.559
I don't make, oh, OK, for many different sensors.

00:13:31.559 --> 00:13:36.099
So I have sensor, sensor, date, temperature.

00:13:36.099 --> 00:13:39.000
It's time to take a new reading.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:43.080
I don't add a new column with a new temperature

00:13:43.080 --> 00:13:43.919
on a different date.

00:13:43.919 --> 00:13:45.400
I add a new row.

00:13:45.400 --> 00:13:51.039
So we have one observation per row, and then one kind of table

00:13:51.039 --> 00:13:52.919
for a kind of observation.

00:13:52.919 --> 00:13:55.000
So these are this idea of tidy data principles.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:56.559
And we can apply them.

00:13:56.559 --> 00:14:01.760
It can be an approach for us to take unstructured text data

00:14:01.760 --> 00:14:04.719
and get it to structured, get it to structured data

00:14:04.719 --> 00:14:08.760
so we can use algorithms and math on it.

00:14:08.760 --> 00:14:14.719
So I work on a main package.

00:14:14.719 --> 00:14:17.760
The main package we'll be using today is called TidyText.

00:14:17.760 --> 00:14:22.000
So TidyText is an R package for text mining

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:24.080
using tidy data principles.

