The first is EDA, which means Exploratory Data Analysis.

00:15:49.159 --> 00:15:52.359
This means we're not training a model.

00:15:52.359 --> 00:15:56.880
We are, instead, we want to summarize, visualize,

00:15:56.880 --> 00:15:57.559
make plots.

00:15:57.559 --> 00:16:03.039
We want to start to understand the content of the text.

00:16:03.039 --> 00:16:05.440
And then after we talk about EDA for text,

00:16:05.440 --> 00:16:07.559
we'll talk about modeling for text,

00:16:07.559 --> 00:16:09.280
building the kinds of models that you

00:16:09.280 --> 00:16:11.479
can build for text data.

00:16:11.479 --> 00:16:15.840
So we'll maybe go to the hour with EDA.

00:16:15.840 --> 00:16:20.200
And then maybe we'll all stand up for five minutes at 5 PM

00:16:20.200 --> 00:16:22.559
and then come back and talk about modeling, maybe

00:16:22.559 --> 00:16:23.640
from 5 to 6 PM.

00:16:23.640 --> 00:16:27.919
So that will be the plan for what we go through today.

00:16:27.919 --> 00:16:33.200
So I was telling you about tidy text, tidy data principles.

00:16:33.200 --> 00:16:37.119
And some of you may think, what are you talking about?

00:16:37.119 --> 00:16:38.119
What do you mean?

00:16:38.119 --> 00:16:40.559
So let's look at an example here.

00:16:40.559 --> 00:16:44.000
So this is the poem, Cantos Nuevos,

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:46.960
by Federico Garcia Lorca.

00:16:46.960 --> 00:16:50.359
And notice, so I have assigned it to a,

00:16:50.359 --> 00:16:52.080
this is just the beginning of the poem.

00:16:52.080 --> 00:16:54.559
And I have assigned it here to a variable here.

00:16:54.559 --> 00:16:58.719
And so notice that this is what we would call a, in R,

00:16:58.719 --> 00:17:00.840
we call this a character vector.

00:17:00.840 --> 00:17:04.599
So it's a vector data structure.

00:17:04.599 --> 00:17:09.079
And it has atomic variables that are

00:17:09.079 --> 00:17:10.680
of type character in them.

00:17:10.680 --> 00:17:14.959
If you are familiar with Python or other tools,

00:17:14.959 --> 00:17:16.560
you may think of them as strings,

00:17:16.560 --> 00:17:19.319
or if you have other strings, characters.

00:17:19.319 --> 00:17:24.000
But notice that it's a vector of length 4.

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:25.319
So this is a vector.

00:17:25.319 --> 00:17:26.920
It has four elements here.

00:17:26.920 --> 00:17:31.839
So this is not yet tidy, meaning we don't have

00:17:31.839 --> 00:17:35.479
one observation per row here.

00:17:35.479 --> 00:17:38.319
Think of this as the unstructured data.

00:17:38.319 --> 00:17:42.359
Now, we can put it into a data frame structure.

00:17:42.359 --> 00:17:47.199
So a table is a modern implementation

00:17:47.199 --> 00:17:48.880
of a data frame here.

00:17:48.880 --> 00:17:52.839
So if I put this into a structure like this,

00:17:52.839 --> 00:17:57.839
we have, now it's starting to be more like a data frame,

00:17:58.199 --> 00:18:01.540
more like a spreadsheet, more like a rectangle.

00:18:01.540 --> 00:18:03.520
So I have two variables.

00:18:03.520 --> 00:18:07.079
One tells me which line of the poem is it.

00:18:07.079 --> 00:18:09.800
And then the other one tells me what is in the poem.

00:18:09.800 --> 00:18:11.619
What is the content of the poem?

00:18:11.619 --> 00:18:15.119
So we're starting to have some richer information,

00:18:15.119 --> 00:18:19.780
but this still, I would say, is not a tidy data set

00:18:19.780 --> 00:18:22.359
when we talk about tidy data principles.

00:18:22.359 --> 00:18:25.119
So we can load the tidy text library

00:18:25.119 --> 00:18:28.280
and then use this function unnest tokens.

00:18:28.280 --> 00:18:32.160
And now here, we have what I want to say

00:18:32.160 --> 00:18:34.579
is tidy data for text.

00:18:34.579 --> 00:18:38.900
So notice that this function is doing several things.

00:18:38.900 --> 00:18:43.099
It is, these are mostly options that you can turn on or off

00:18:43.099 --> 00:18:46.459
depending on your particular needs or analysis.

00:18:46.459 --> 00:18:48.579
But notice that instead of having,

00:18:48.579 --> 00:18:53.579
instead of having one row per line,

00:18:54.260 --> 00:18:57.540
now I have one row per word.

00:18:57.540 --> 00:19:00.939
So this is called tokenization,

00:19:00.939 --> 00:19:04.839
where we take text and we divide it into tokens.

00:19:04.839 --> 00:19:08.180
The most common token when we work with text

00:19:08.180 --> 00:19:09.540
is a single word.

00:19:09.540 --> 00:19:11.420
So the process of tokenization

00:19:11.420 --> 00:19:14.979
is the process of identifying what are the words,

00:19:14.979 --> 00:19:16.680
where do I break them apart?

00:19:16.680 --> 00:19:20.520
We also did a little bit of some text processing

00:19:20.520 --> 00:19:24.020
to make it easier for us to analyze it later.

00:19:24.020 --> 00:19:27.739
We got rid of capitalization.

00:19:27.739 --> 00:19:30.540
We took some steps so that we got rid of punctuation

00:19:30.540 --> 00:19:31.619
between words.

00:19:31.619 --> 00:19:35.500
These again are options you may want to keep or you may not,

00:19:35.500 --> 00:19:37.780
but these are the defaults here.

00:19:37.780 --> 00:19:42.500
So we've transformed our data from unstructured

00:19:42.500 --> 00:19:44.339
to now structured.

00:19:44.339 --> 00:19:48.140
Notice that I still know which word

00:19:48.140 --> 00:19:50.660
came from which line in the poem.

00:19:50.660 --> 00:19:54.540
So when we tokenize text and transform its shape

00:19:54.540 --> 00:19:56.359
so that it's in the tidy data still,

00:19:56.359 --> 00:19:57.979
we still know things like

00:19:57.979 --> 00:19:59.619
all the other information we have.

00:20:00.619 --> 00:20:03.219
If we had other columns here,

00:20:03.219 --> 00:20:04.900
not just the line of the poem,

00:20:04.900 --> 00:20:07.260
but other information about that text,

00:20:07.260 --> 00:20:08.300
we keep it all.

00:20:08.300 --> 00:20:10.219
We keep it all as we move forward.

00:20:10.219 --> 00:20:13.380
So we have one observation per row.

00:20:13.380 --> 00:20:16.640
So that's a tiny, tiny little example,

00:20:16.640 --> 00:20:18.420
just four lines of a poem.

00:20:19.339 --> 00:20:22.020
So this is the function that does all this.

