Everything else is from a set of tools

00:27:47.800 --> 00:27:51.040
that is built for working with quantitative data.

00:27:51.040 --> 00:27:55.739
All right, so now I'm no great Spanish speaker,

00:27:55.739 --> 00:27:59.660
but I look at this and even I know,

00:27:59.660 --> 00:28:01.760
those are not very interesting words.

00:28:01.760 --> 00:28:03.400
Those are not very interesting words.

00:28:03.400 --> 00:28:08.119
When you take any collection of text data,

00:28:08.119 --> 00:28:12.040
natural text, and you count up what's the most common,

00:28:12.040 --> 00:28:14.719
the most common words are very boring.

00:28:14.719 --> 00:28:16.760
They're usually not important

00:28:16.760 --> 00:28:20.160
for the analytical purposes you have,

00:28:20.160 --> 00:28:24.359
and we have a word for what they're called in text analysis,

00:28:24.359 --> 00:28:26.500
and what it's called is stop words.

00:28:26.500 --> 00:28:28.239
They're called stop words.

00:28:28.239 --> 00:28:30.979
So stop words, if you hear stop words,

00:28:30.979 --> 00:28:33.119
it's a word that usually means like,

00:28:33.800 --> 00:28:35.800
it's not important, it's very common,

00:28:35.800 --> 00:28:37.800
it's not very informative.

00:28:37.800 --> 00:28:42.800
It's there to make the structure of the sentences

00:28:43.119 --> 00:28:44.880
so that we can understand each other,

00:28:44.880 --> 00:28:47.560
but they're not very specific, usually,

00:28:47.560 --> 00:28:50.760
to the kind of data that we want to deal with.

00:28:50.760 --> 00:28:55.760
So there are data sets of stop words that are available.

00:28:57.959 --> 00:29:00.800
It's important to know or to ask the question,

00:29:00.800 --> 00:29:03.160
where did these data sets come from?

00:29:03.160 --> 00:29:06.640
These data sets are, there's a bunch of them.

00:29:06.640 --> 00:29:10.959
This one, the default one, is from a lexicon,

00:29:12.199 --> 00:29:15.479
excuse me, from a lexicon called Snowball,

00:29:15.479 --> 00:29:20.479
which is an old software for analyzing text,

00:29:20.719 --> 00:29:24.680
and they include a list of stop words there,

00:29:24.680 --> 00:29:27.560
but there are many different data sets of stop words.

00:29:27.560 --> 00:29:30.099
Often, the way that they were created,

00:29:30.579 --> 00:29:32.579
these lists are usually pretty old.

00:29:32.579 --> 00:29:34.619
The way that they're created

00:29:34.619 --> 00:29:38.859
is you take some big collection of language,

00:29:38.859 --> 00:29:41.000
big, not one book, many books,

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:42.859
and you add up the most common words,

00:29:42.859 --> 00:29:45.819
and you pick a line, and you say,

00:29:45.819 --> 00:29:49.500
okay, these are the stop words, and these are not,

00:29:49.500 --> 00:29:54.300
so you, or you compare across many different collections,

00:29:54.300 --> 00:29:56.900
and you say, what are the common ones, like this?

00:29:56.900 --> 00:29:59.380
So this is an English list of stop words

00:29:59.380 --> 00:30:01.420
that's somewhat conservative.

00:30:01.420 --> 00:30:03.079
It's somewhat small.

00:30:03.079 --> 00:30:04.280
It's not so big.

00:30:05.619 --> 00:30:07.859
They are not only for English.

00:30:07.859 --> 00:30:10.719
There are data sets for other languages as well.

00:30:10.719 --> 00:30:12.540
Notice this one is a bit bigger,

00:30:12.540 --> 00:30:15.760
