I can kind of learn what this is about.

00:46:14.452 --> 00:46:19.252
And then over here we have, you know, these interesting people� you know, these characters

00:46:19.252 --> 00:46:20.252
here.

00:46:20.252 --> 00:46:21.973
So think about a different application.

00:46:21.973 --> 00:46:28.613
If you have survey results, you could� what TFIDF helps us do is identify things that

00:46:28.613 --> 00:46:33.372
are important in one document compared to another document.

00:46:33.372 --> 00:46:35.293
It's not the only way to do this.

00:46:35.293 --> 00:46:39.093
So we just talked about this term frequency.

00:46:39.093 --> 00:46:45.293
But another way that I find very impactful for this kind of work is what's called a weighted

00:46:45.293 --> 00:46:46.932
log odds.

00:46:46.932 --> 00:46:49.372
Now we're not even really to models yet.

00:46:49.372 --> 00:46:54.332
But we're starting to have a little bit more sophistication in what we're doing.

00:46:54.332 --> 00:47:01.413
So I imagine that you all are familiar that a log odds ratio tells us a probability.

00:47:01.413 --> 00:47:09.392
And we can weight the probabilities because we know� we know the distribution of words.

00:47:09.392 --> 00:47:13.973
So remember that some words are super common.

00:47:13.973 --> 00:47:15.932
Other words are more rare.

00:47:15.932 --> 00:47:25.132
And we want to weight the� we want to weight the log odds ratio by how sure we are that

00:47:25.132 --> 00:47:27.533
what we're seeing is a real difference.

00:47:27.533 --> 00:47:32.932
So let's say� let's say we have some words that are very common.

00:47:32.932 --> 00:47:36.372
Like and and K. You know?

00:47:36.372 --> 00:47:42.653
If we see a difference in those words, a big difference, we know that is real.

00:47:42.853 --> 00:47:47.252
Let's say there's a word that appears one time in one book and doesn't appear in the

00:47:47.252 --> 00:47:48.293
other book.

00:47:48.293 --> 00:47:52.132
We cannot be so certain that that's a significant difference.

00:47:52.132 --> 00:47:53.132
We have to weight.

00:47:53.132 --> 00:47:58.132
Because natural language exhibits a power law distribution.

00:47:58.132 --> 00:48:05.353
It's� you know, we� if you plot it on a log log scale, we see that some words we

00:48:05.353 --> 00:48:08.812
use many times and other words we use very little.

00:48:08.812 --> 00:48:13.892
It's a characteristic of text data that we have this power law distribution.

00:48:13.892 --> 00:48:20.913
And so when we use weighted log odds, it helps us to get a good answer for� a good answer

00:48:20.913 --> 00:48:26.773
for which words have a higher probability from coming from one document for the others.

00:48:26.773 --> 00:48:31.053
For those of you who are statisticians in the bunch, the typical way of doing weighted

00:48:31.053 --> 00:48:33.733
log odds is with empirical Bayes.

00:48:33.733 --> 00:48:38.053
So empirical Bayes, maybe we're starting to say is a model, you know?

00:48:38.053 --> 00:48:43.332
But it just uses the data itself to be able to� to be able to do the weighting, to be

00:48:43.332 --> 00:48:46.093
able to say what is the distribution that we would have.

00:48:46.093 --> 00:48:51.053
So we're maybe starting to get into using some modeling, but not so much.

00:48:51.053 --> 00:48:58.713
So it looks just the same as a bind TFIDF, whereas here we're doing bind log odds.

00:48:58.713 --> 00:49:03.293
It is in another package, in tidy load, because this actually works great, not just for text

00:49:03.293 --> 00:49:08.732
data, but for many kinds of data that we can do this kind of weighted log odds.

00:49:08.732 --> 00:49:13.852
Anytime we have, like, a power law distribution, it's a really great application.

00:49:13.852 --> 00:49:15.693
Definitely true in text that we have that.

00:49:15.693 --> 00:49:18.232
So this is a different statistic.

00:49:18.232 --> 00:49:21.773
So the statistic before was TFIDF.

00:49:21.773 --> 00:49:27.732
It's a heuristic statistic, but it's one that we can measure for a word in a document in

00:49:27.732 --> 00:49:29.673
a collection of documents.

00:49:29.673 --> 00:49:32.173
This is a different thing we can measure, the log odds.

00:49:32.193 --> 00:49:36.193
So it gives us� you'll notice here we have some similar results.

00:49:36.193 --> 00:49:42.053
You know, eugenia, you said, panza, you know, Dulcinea, we have some similar words.

00:49:42.053 --> 00:49:50.173
But it� so it's a� it's a different approach, but the� the main difference is that weighted

00:49:50.173 --> 00:49:56.732
log odds can distinguish between words that are used in all documents, in all text.

00:49:56.793 --> 00:50:02.472
So remember that when we had K in all three of the books, it went down to zero.

00:50:02.472 --> 00:50:07.592
But a weighted log odds allows us to distinguish between words that are in all the text.

00:50:07.592 --> 00:50:13.073
And they do sometimes� you can say, oh, this word is much more important in this document

00:50:13.073 --> 00:50:17.793
than this document, even if it is in all the documents.

00:50:17.793 --> 00:50:20.153
