01:02:50.153 --> 01:02:56.033
So the way that the most common kinds of models work for topic modeling is that each document

01:02:56.033 --> 01:02:58.953
that we have is a mixture of topics.

01:02:58.953 --> 01:03:01.913
And then each topic is a mixture of words.

01:03:01.913 --> 01:03:07.112
So if you had survey responses, you could imagine maybe� maybe you're trying to learn

01:03:07.112 --> 01:03:09.033
what topics there are.

01:03:09.033 --> 01:03:13.352
And in all� any� so say we're trying� with some of the topics, let's say we're thinking

01:03:13.352 --> 01:03:18.153
about survey responses from student evaluations at a university.

01:03:18.153 --> 01:03:25.392
Some of the topics could be the tests, the homework, the lectures.

01:03:25.392 --> 01:03:31.073
And the� each survey response can be about all of those things in some mixture.

01:03:31.073 --> 01:03:35.193
And then each topic uses a variety of words.

01:03:35.193 --> 01:03:37.392
And you can have the same words in different topics.

01:03:37.913 --> 01:03:44.913
So underneath, this is� it's called� it's like multi� like, you know, Gaussian multilevel

01:03:44.913 --> 01:03:45.913
modeling.

01:03:45.913 --> 01:03:48.592
But this is the main idea that we need to have about what these models are about.

01:03:42.120 --> 01:03:45.020
Which means we have to have a framework .

01:03:45.020 --> 01:03:49.480
So topic modeling is an example of unsupervised machine learning.

01:03:49.480 --> 01:03:57.960
So we have a label on the document and we're trying to predict, we're not trying to predict

01:03:57.960 --> 01:03:58.960
yes no.

01:03:58.960 --> 01:04:01.600
Instead of we don't have any labels.

01:04:01.600 --> 01:04:03.880
We're doing unsupervised machine learning here.

01:04:03.880 --> 01:04:07.380
So that's the kind of model that topic modeling is.

01:04:07.380 --> 01:04:13.499
Here is an example back from my Stack Overflow days, a real example of topic modeling.

