you have it there for, to be able to do this yourself.

01:23:46.739 --> 01:23:53.620
So when we build models, I said this in the last section, we take, we need a, we need

01:23:53.620 --> 01:23:54.620
a matrix.

01:23:54.620 --> 01:24:00.699
We need a matrix to be able to do linear algebra on the, to do, to build some kind of model

01:24:00.699 --> 01:24:01.699
here.

01:24:01.699 --> 01:24:09.180
The, the matrix that you make is typically very sparse.

01:24:09.180 --> 01:24:15.260
It is a very high dimensionality and it can have a huge number of features.

01:24:15.260 --> 01:24:23.859
So natural language, we tend to have most documents do not use most words.

01:24:23.859 --> 01:24:26.579
So the data is very sparse.

01:24:26.579 --> 01:24:32.020
This, this cheese data is about 95% sparse.

01:24:32.020 --> 01:24:36.140
That means 95% of the spaces are zero.

01:24:36.140 --> 01:24:43.099
If you have a matrix where you say, here's tangy, here's sweet, and then the cheeses

01:24:43.099 --> 01:24:48.819
on the, the rows are the cheese and the columns are the flavors, the words to describe the

01:24:48.819 --> 01:24:49.819
flavors.

01:24:49.819 --> 01:24:53.219
It's 95% just zeros.

01:24:53.579 --> 01:25:00.579
So that's actually not so sparse for, if you had natural language, it would be 99.99% sparse.

01:25:00.579 --> 01:25:04.380
Very sparse, very high dimensionality.

01:25:04.380 --> 01:25:11.219
Notice that I have, notice that I have a thousand documents.

01:25:11.219 --> 01:25:17.579
So that's a thousand cheeses and 46 features with, that's, you know, that's, that's getting

01:25:17.579 --> 01:25:22.699
to be, maybe that's medium dimensionality, but it's a lot of columns.

01:25:22.699 --> 01:25:24.540
46 columns is a lot of columns.

01:25:24.540 --> 01:25:30.300
For real language, it could be, if you have 10,000 documents, your rows could be, could

01:25:30.300 --> 01:25:31.620
be 10,000, actually.

01:25:31.620 --> 01:25:32.620
It could be 1,000.

01:25:32.620 --> 01:25:36.660
High, high dimensionality.

01:25:36.660 --> 01:25:37.660
It's a big problem.

01:25:37.660 --> 01:25:42.099
This is a big problem for training models with language.

01:25:42.099 --> 01:25:48.819
And this is where word embeddings are used, because if we think about it, words are not

01:25:48.819 --> 01:25:51.339
used in each other randomly.

01:25:51.339 --> 01:25:52.500
They're not independent.

01:25:53.300 --> 01:25:58.099
So if you come from a statistics background, these are not independent of each other.

01:25:58.099 --> 01:26:01.699
In fact, they are used together in specific ways.

01:26:01.699 --> 01:26:07.339
They're, like, when I say a sentence to you, it's not just words, I don't just choose words

01:26:07.339 --> 01:26:09.339
randomly and put them in a sentence to you.

01:26:09.339 --> 01:26:12.579
I use rules about how I speak.

01:26:12.579 --> 01:26:19.579
And this sentence is, this quote is from someone named John Rupert Firth, who back, like, in

01:26:19.660 --> 01:26:26.660
the 1950s was a linguist who talked about word embeddings in an abstract idea.

01:26:26.660 --> 01:26:34.979
Like, they didn't really have them to use, but he had this idea that we can make an embedding.

01:26:34.979 --> 01:26:38.540
So think of embedding equals vector.

01:26:38.540 --> 01:26:40.040
Embedding equals vector.

01:26:40.040 --> 01:26:48.620
So I want to make a column of numbers that will represent the text, because I know, say,

01:26:48.620 --> 01:26:58.380
when I'm talking to you with some words, I use the words together in a way that there

01:26:58.380 --> 01:27:04.339
are rules about how the words are used, and we want to try to learn those rules.

01:27:04.339 --> 01:27:05.339
Okay.

01:27:05.339 --> 01:27:14.939
So you have probably heard of some of these things, because these are all now a part of

01:27:14.939 --> 01:27:16.020
our lives.

01:27:16.020 --> 01:27:24.739
So maybe 10 years ago, word embeddings were things called Word2Vec, GloVe, FastText.

01:27:24.739 --> 01:27:27.180
This is like 10 years ago, word embeddings.

01:27:27.180 --> 01:27:36.219
These are algorithms for taking a text, a set of text, and learning the matrix representation

01:27:36.219 --> 01:27:38.819
for how the words go together.

01:27:38.819 --> 01:27:43.180
So think of it like if you were a statistician or have a statistics background, think of

01:27:43.180 --> 01:27:47.859
it like PCA, but fancy.

01:27:47.859 --> 01:27:52.979
I have a high-dimensional space, and I need to learn a lower-dimensional kind of space.

01:27:52.979 --> 01:27:58.859
And so these are all rules, rules for using linear algebra to go from a super high-dimensional

01:27:58.859 --> 01:28:04.339
space to a lower-dimensional space, and then I can represent words and documents in this

01:28:04.339 --> 01:28:05.339
space.

01:28:05.339 --> 01:28:14.260
So now there are companies out there who have taken enormous data sets of text and are learning

01:28:14.260 --> 01:28:18.699
these representations, these embedding representations.

01:28:18.699 --> 01:28:24.420
All LLMs are built on the infrastructure of embeddings.

01:28:24.420 --> 01:28:36.900
So you can go to OpenAI and get an API token, and then you can send text to OpenAI, and

01:28:36.900 --> 01:28:41.660
they will send back to you the embeddings using their embeddings there.

01:28:41.660 --> 01:28:45.239
And so what you will get back is a long string of numbers.

01:28:45.239 --> 01:28:54.099
So it's a way to represent a text or a document numerically based on the rules of how text

01:28:54.099 --> 01:28:57.939
is used together, that it's not just random what words go together.

01:28:57.939 --> 01:29:05.660
So now I highly recommend that you read this if you are interested in embeddings.

