01:30:04.280 --> 01:30:08.559
And then we are going to use the glove embeddings...

01:30:08.559 --> 01:30:12.079
The glove algorithm to learn word embeddings.

01:30:12.079 --> 01:30:16.579
And glove is available in the word salad package.

01:30:16.579 --> 01:30:19.479
So what we're doing here is we're saying...

01:30:19.479 --> 01:30:21.920
I have all these cheeses.

01:30:21.920 --> 01:30:26.040
I have the flavors of them that are described using words.

01:30:26.040 --> 01:30:30.880
Let me use glove to learn how the words are used together.

01:30:30.880 --> 01:30:36.719
So think of glove here as like PCA.

01:30:36.719 --> 01:30:37.719
Like in analogy.

01:30:37.719 --> 01:30:39.400
I mean, not in detail.

01:30:39.400 --> 01:30:40.400
But in analogy.

01:30:40.400 --> 01:30:42.559
So let's say we have a high dimensional space.

01:30:42.559 --> 01:30:44.880
And I'm going to learn a...

01:30:44.880 --> 01:30:45.880
I think I did 10.

01:30:45.880 --> 01:30:46.880
10 dimensions.

01:30:46.880 --> 01:30:47.880
Yes.

01:30:47.880 --> 01:30:50.520
So I did 10.

01:30:50.520 --> 01:30:55.880
So let's make 10...

01:30:55.880 --> 01:30:58.839
I have, you know, 1,000 or I think it was 50.

01:30:58.839 --> 01:31:02.160
I have 50 dimensional space.

01:31:02.160 --> 01:31:05.120
And I want to learn a lower 10 dimensional space.

01:31:05.160 --> 01:31:13.000
So think of the analogy here is that open AI got the whole internet and for months and

01:31:13.000 --> 01:31:17.800
months chugged with a computer to learn 1,000 dimensional representation.

01:31:17.800 --> 01:31:24.359
So it's like what we're doing here is like a small example compared to the embeddings

01:31:24.359 --> 01:31:28.120
that are used in all of these LLMs here.

01:31:28.120 --> 01:31:29.780
And the tokens that we have...

01:31:29.780 --> 01:31:30.780
This is the things.

01:31:30.780 --> 01:31:31.780
Vegetal.

01:31:31.780 --> 01:31:32.780
Tart.

01:31:32.780 --> 01:31:33.780
Meaty.

01:31:33.780 --> 01:31:34.780
Floral.

01:31:35.439 --> 01:31:37.260
So these are the tokens here.

01:31:37.260 --> 01:31:39.059
And these are the embeddings.

01:31:39.059 --> 01:31:41.819
These are the vectors here.

01:31:41.819 --> 01:31:42.819
Yes.

01:31:42.819 --> 01:31:43.819
Okay.

01:31:43.819 --> 01:31:48.900
And so now for every cheese, we can find...

01:31:48.900 --> 01:31:49.900
So those were...

01:31:49.900 --> 01:31:50.900
That was the...

01:31:50.900 --> 01:31:51.900
We have all these words.

01:31:51.900 --> 01:31:54.819
I want to learn a lower dimensional space.

01:31:54.819 --> 01:32:01.780
Now for every cheese, we can find a mean cheese.

01:32:01.780 --> 01:32:02.780
So these are cheese embeddings.

01:32:03.780 --> 01:32:06.780
This might be the first time anyone has ever made cheese embeddings.

01:32:06.780 --> 01:32:07.780
No, probably not.

01:32:07.780 --> 01:32:10.540
So what we're doing is we are...

01:32:10.540 --> 01:32:11.900
We use unnest tokens.

01:32:11.900 --> 01:32:13.900
We're back to tidy data.

01:32:13.900 --> 01:32:17.099
And we join in the flavor embeddings.

01:32:17.099 --> 01:32:18.140
And then I'm gonna...

01:32:18.140 --> 01:32:20.380
For every cheese that I have...

01:32:20.380 --> 01:32:24.300
And I will keep around the country and the type and all that kind of thing.

01:32:24.300 --> 01:32:25.979
I'm gonna take the mean.

01:32:25.979 --> 01:32:28.099
So if there were...

01:32:28.099 --> 01:32:29.300
There are different ways of...

01:32:29.859 --> 01:32:34.500
If you have a document made of words, there are different ways of getting a document embedding

01:32:34.500 --> 01:32:37.059
from a set of word embeddings.

01:32:37.059 --> 01:32:38.380
Mean is one of the ways to do it.

01:32:38.380 --> 01:32:41.260
You can also do other ways of waiting here.

01:32:41.260 --> 01:32:42.579
So these are cheese embeddings.

01:32:42.579 --> 01:32:46.939
So for every cheese that I have, where is it in this 10 dimensional space?

01:32:46.939 --> 01:32:50.900
So I had a high dimensional space of all the words for flavors.

01:32:50.900 --> 01:32:52.739
I made a lower dimensional space.

01:32:52.739 --> 01:32:56.300
And then I found where in the lower dimensional space are all the cheeses?

01:32:56.300 --> 01:32:58.300
Are all the cheeses?

01:32:58.579 --> 01:33:00.260
Okay.

01:33:00.260 --> 01:33:04.859
And now I can find cheese similarities.

01:33:04.859 --> 01:33:08.459
So this is just cosine.

01:33:08.459 --> 01:33:10.380
This is just cosine similarity.

01:33:10.380 --> 01:33:11.500
So for all of the...

01:33:11.500 --> 01:33:12.500
In this...

01:33:12.500 --> 01:33:14.380
I have this space.

01:33:14.380 --> 01:33:17.380
I have all these cheeses in this 10 dimensional space.

01:33:17.380 --> 01:33:19.260
And I find out which...

01:33:19.260 --> 01:33:22.180
I compute cosine similarity for all the cheeses.

01:33:22.180 --> 01:33:28.059
To say which cheeses are close together in the words that are used to describe them.

01:33:28.099 --> 01:33:30.219
And which cheeses are far apart.

01:33:30.219 --> 01:33:33.339
So think about the analogy here is...

01:33:33.339 --> 01:33:35.219
You can use embeddings in many ways.

01:33:35.219 --> 01:33:39.459
The LLMs use them to, you know, to say...

01:33:39.459 --> 01:33:40.459
To make a sentence.

01:33:40.459 --> 01:33:41.459
Saying...

01:33:41.459 --> 01:33:42.459
Okay.

01:33:42.459 --> 01:33:43.900
If I need to keep...

01:33:43.900 --> 01:33:44.900
Like chat...

01:33:44.900 --> 01:33:46.300
You ask chatGPT something.

01:33:46.300 --> 01:33:47.300
And chatGPT says...

01:33:47.300 --> 01:33:48.300
Okay.

01:33:48.300 --> 01:33:49.300
Time to make an answer.

01:33:49.300 --> 01:33:50.979
I'll say...

01:33:50.979 --> 01:33:52.900
What is the next most common word?

01:33:52.900 --> 01:33:57.979
And then it uses embeddings like this to be able to keep next word, next word, next word.

01:33:58.140 --> 01:34:00.260
Because we find things that are close together.

01:34:00.260 --> 01:34:01.260
And we're able to say...

01:34:01.260 --> 01:34:03.939
What is the next most common word?

01:34:03.939 --> 01:34:07.420
But we can use embeddings in many ways.

01:34:07.420 --> 01:34:11.300
One of the ways is by finding things that are similar to each other.

01:34:11.300 --> 01:34:12.500
So this is...

01:34:12.500 --> 01:34:20.900
So this matrix contains the similarity scores for each cheese compared to each other cheese

01:34:20.900 --> 01:34:22.280
here.

01:34:22.280 --> 01:34:23.540
So let's say...

01:34:23.540 --> 01:34:26.780
I'm enjoying my trip to Spain very much.

